4. Influence functions

4.1 The idea: how much does each observation matter?
Imagine removing observation \(i\) from the dataset and re-estimating \(\hat\theta\). The change \(\hat\theta_{(-i)} - \hat\theta\) tells you how much observation \(i\) “influenced” the estimate. The influence function (IF) is the first-order approximation to this quantity, scaled by \(n\):
\[
\text{IF}_i \approx -n(\hat\theta_{(-i)} - \hat\theta)
\]
But we do not need to actually refit the model \(n\) times. For M-estimators, the IF can be computed in closed form.


4.2 Deriving the IF from the linearisation
In Section 1.4, Step 1, we derived the linearisation:
\[
\underset{p \times 1}{\hat\beta - \beta_0}
\;\approx\;
\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n
\underset{p \times p}{\color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}}}
\;\;
\underset{p \times 1}{\psi(O_i; \beta_0)}
\]
Each summand \(\color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}}\psi_i\) is the contribution of observation \(i\) to the total estimation error. This is exactly the influence function:
\[
\underset{p \times 1}{\text{IF}_i}
\;=\;
\underset{p \times p}{\color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}}}
\;\cdot\;
\underset{p \times 1}{\psi(O_i; \hat\beta)}
\tag{3}\]
Reading each factor:

\(\psi_i\) (\(p \times 1\)): the score from Section 1.2 — how much observation \(i\)’s data “disagrees” with the current \(\hat\beta\).
\(\color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}}\) (\(p \times p\)): the bread inverse from Section 1.4 — converts from score-space to parameter-space, accounting for curvature.
\(\text{IF}_i\) (\(p \times 1\)): the resulting shift in \(\hat\beta\) attributable to observation \(i\) (times \(n\)).

No new derivation is needed. The IF is the linearisation, read term-by-term.


4.3 Two properties that make IFs useful
Property 1: Linearisation. The IF lets us write a complex estimator as a simple average:
\[
\hat\beta - \beta_0 \approx \frac{1}{n}\sum_i \text{IF}_i
\]
Property 2: Variance recovery. Since \(E[\text{IF}_i] = 0\):
\[
\text{Var}(\hat\beta) \approx
\frac{1}{n^2}\sum_i \text{IF}_i \, \text{IF}_i^T
\]
Expanding \(\text{IF}_i \text{IF}_i^T = \color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}} \psi_i
\psi_i^T \color{#3182BD}{(A^{-1})^T}\) and factoring:
\[
\frac{1}{n^2}\sum_i \color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}} \psi_i\psi_i^T
\color{#3182BD}{(A^{-1})^T}
= \frac{1}{n} \color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}}
\underbrace{\frac{1}{n}\sum_i \psi_i\psi_i^T}_
{\color{#E6550D}{B}\text{ (the meat)}}
\color{#3182BD}{(A^{-1})^T}
\]
This is the sandwich from Section 1.4.






NoteThe key equivalence



\[
\underbrace{\frac{1}{n^2}\sum_i \text{IF}_i\,\text{IF}_i^T}_
{\text{IF-based variance}}
\;=\;
\underbrace{\frac{1}{n}\,\color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}}\,\color{#E6550D}{B}\,
\color{#3182BD}{(A^{-1})^T}}_{\text{sandwich variance}}
\tag{4}\]
The sandwich operates on matrices. The IF operates on per-individual vectors. Same answer, different representation.




4.4 Example: IF for a sample mean
\(\hat\mu = \frac{1}{n}\sum_i Y_i\). Estimating equation: \(\psi(O_i; \mu)
= Y_i - \mu\). Bread: \(A = 1\). IF: \(\text{IF}_i = Y_i - \hat\mu\). Variance: \(\frac{1}{n^2}\sum_i(Y_i - \hat\mu)^2 = s^2/n\).


4.5 Example: IF for g-computation (the two-channel derivation)
The g-computation marginal mean is a two-step estimator: first estimate \(\hat\beta\), then compute \(\hat\mu_a = \frac{1}{n}\sum_i g^{-1}(X_i^{*T}
\hat\beta)\). Individual \(i\) affects \(\hat\mu_a\) through two channels.

Channel 1: Direct contribution
Even if \(\hat\beta\) were fixed, observation \(i\)’s prediction \(g^{-1}(X_i^{*T}\hat\beta)\) is one of the \(n\) terms being averaged:
\[
\text{IF}_i^{\text{direct}} = g^{-1}(X_i^{*T}\hat\beta) - \hat\mu_a
\qquad (\text{scalar})
\]


Channel 2: Indirect contribution (via \(\hat\beta\))
Observation \(i\) shifts \(\hat\beta\) by approximately \(\frac{1}{n}
\color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}}\psi_i\) (from Section 4.2). This shift changes \(\hat\mu_a\) by:
\[
\delta\hat\mu_a \;\approx\;
\underset{1 \times p}{\color{#31A354}{J_a}}
\;\cdot\;
\underset{p \times 1}{\frac{1}{n}\color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}}\psi_i}
\]
where \(\color{#31A354}{J_a}\) (\(1 \times p\)) is the Jacobian from Section 2.3.


Combining both channels
\[
\text{IF}_i(\hat\mu_a) =
\underbrace{g^{-1}(X_i^{*T}\hat\beta) - \hat\mu_a}_
{\text{Channel 1 (scalar)}}
\;+\;
\underbrace{
\underset{1 \times p}{\color{#31A354}{J_a}}
\;\;
\underset{p \times p}{\color{#3182BD}{A^{-1}}}
\;\;
\underset{p \times 1}{\psi_i}
}_{\text{Channel 2 (scalar)}}
\tag{5}\]
Why two channels matter: Channel 1 alone would treat \(\hat\beta\) as fixed — ignoring estimation uncertainty. Channel 2 adds the uncertainty propagated from the model fit. This is the \(\color{#31A354}{J} V_\beta
\color{#31A354}{J^T}\) term from Section 2, now expressed per-individual.



4.6 Why influence functions matter for multi-model estimators
For a single-model estimator, the IF is equivalent to \(\color{#31A354}{J} V_\beta \color{#31A354}{J^T}\) — useful but not essential. IFs become necessary for multi-model estimators:

Compositional: IFs from different models can be summed to get the total IF. No large joint covariance matrix needed.
Covariance for free: \(\text{Cov}(\hat\mu_a, \hat\mu_b)
= \frac{1}{n^2}\sum_i \text{IF}_i^{(a)} \cdot \text{IF}_i^{(b)}\).
Diagnostics: large \(|\text{IF}_i|\) flags influential observations.
